b'@bizalmanac Landscaping is v disorganized and it\xe2\x80\x99s difficult to get purchasing orgs in line. Mostly a $SITE vs Ewing decision with some pretty strong feelings. Not my favorite distribution space'
b'@bizalmanac @scuttleblurb has a solid write up on $SITE and other distributors'

b'RT @COValueInvestor: @bizalmanac For most suburban residents, COVID raised incomes (through stimulus pmts) and much of that $ was put into\xe2\x80\xa6'

b'@bizalmanac For most suburban residents, COVID raised incomes (through stimulus pmts) and much of that $ was put into home improvement (see $HD, $LOW results). We happen to think that provided a tailwind that masks the underlying poor economics at $SITE, but we could be wrong.'

b"@bizalmanac We've visited several in western US, most were acquired. In many cases, acquired biz didn't have the footprint that $SITE wants, so they move the operation to a much bigger piece of land. Land costs are high, inventory costs are enormous, huge labor component."
b'RT @bizalmanac: Looking for feedback on Site One, $SITE, business and investment thesis, a 5% position for me\n\n-Largest supplier of landsca\xe2\x80\xa6'

b"@bizalmanac Have you visited many of their locations? US is in the midst of a move to suburbs that is clearly helping builders and suppliers (and landscaping is a big cost for suburban new builds). Without that tailwind, it's hard for us to see how $SITE locations generate economic profit."

b'Looking for feedback on Site One, $SITE, business and investment thesis, a 5% position for me

-Largest supplier of landscaping supplies in US
-Spends 100% of FCF on acq.
- Assuming 3% organic sales growth, ~100% FCF used for acq. and 50bps of margin expansion/yr,
-I see 20% IRRs'
